#Data Quality Check

# Clean up "fake nulls"
df = df.replace(["", " ", "NA", "N/A", "NULL", "null"], np.nan)

def data_quality_report(df, cols):
    report = pd.DataFrame({
        "Column": cols,
        "Missing Count": [df[c].isna().sum() for c in cols],
        "Missing %": [df[c].isna().mean() * 100 for c in cols]
    })
    return report

# Run for key columns again
quality_report = data_quality_report(df, ["Market", "Product", "Sales Order Line Item ID"])
print("Data Quality Report:\n", quality_report)

# Save to Excel for sharing- ignoring for now as the data is already marked in excel

# Helper function: get top 5 for a given column grouped by Order Type
def top_by_order_type(df, group_col, value_col="Sum of Gross Revenue", top_n=10):
    result = (
        df.groupby(["Order Type", group_col])[value_col]
          .sum()
          .reset_index()
          .sort_values(["Order Type", value_col], ascending=[True, False])
          .groupby("Order Type")
          .head(top_n)
    )
    return result

# Top 10 Markets by Order Type
top_markets = top_by_order_type(df, "Market")

# Helper plotting function -AI assist for Visual
def plot_top_by_order_type(df, group_col, title):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
    sns.barplot(
        data=df,
        x="Order Type", 
        y="Sum of Gross Revenue", 
        hue=group_col, 
        palette="Set2"
    )
    plt.title(f"Top 5 {group_col}s by Order Type")
    plt.ylabel("Revenue")
    plt.xlabel("Order Type")
    plt.legend(title=group_col, bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc="upper left")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Plot each
plot_top_by_order_type(top_markets, "Market", "Markets")
plot_top_by_order_type(top_advertisers, "Advertiser", "Advertisers")
plot_top_by_order_type(top_sellers, "Sales Lead", "Sellers")
plot_top_by_order_type(top_products, "Product", "Products")

Top 5 Market Graph¶

For Local market, the focus should be on LA, NYC and Houston, as these 3 have the highest revenue. For MMP, it should focus on LA, followed by Pheonix and then Bay Area, CA. Lastly for national, we should implement a better identifier that can categorize the Unknown category (for whatever reason, when reruning the notebook, Unknown was replaced with TECHNOLOGY&DIGITALVENTURES). This will help with better targeting on a National level. If we take into account the Local trend, the National should be similar.

Top 5 Advertiser Graph¶

At Local level, Advertisers 4581, 185 and 477 are bringing in the most revenue. However at an MMP level,it is Advertiser 179, which is leaps and bound ahead of the rest of the MMP level advertiser. We should try to understand why that is the case to improve the rest of MMP. For National level, it seems that Advertiser 477 and 4962 are taking the lead. Advertiser 477 is also on the lead at a Local level as well, so they should be studied more in depth.

Top 5 Seller Graph¶

The top 3 sellers at Local levels are Seller 467, 393 and 1330, but all top 5 are relatively close to each other, within 50k USD. At an MMP level, it is seller 236 and 1126 are at leads, so these sellers should be the primary focus for maintaining high revenues. At National level, all sellers appear to be evenly matched but seller 1330 seems to have a lead (it could also be seller 902, due to the colors being so similar. An in depth look is required).

Top 5 Products Graph¶

For products, at Local and MMP level, Broadcast performs best. For local it makes sense as broadcast is the easiest way to reach the most users. While broadcast is still the best for MMP, Podcast is not far behind, showing that multi-market partnership has a strong growth with podcast. The same rule applies to National for Podcast, and streaming which lines up with easier access due to internet accesibility.

Noting that National MMP was excluded for all above, as it does not show any significance revenue possibility.¶

# Helper function: get bottom N for a given column grouped by Order Type
def bottom_by_order_type(df, group_col, value_col="Sum of Gross Revenue", bottom_n=5):
    result = (
        df.groupby(["Order Type", group_col])[value_col]
          .sum()
          .reset_index()
          .sort_values(["Order Type", value_col], ascending=[True, True])  # ascending=True keeps lowest first
          .groupby("Order Type")
          .head(bottom_n)
    )
    return result

# Bottom 5 Markets by Order Type
bottom_markets = bottom_by_order_type(df, "Market")

# Bottom 5 Advertisers by Order Type
bottom_advertisers = bottom_by_order_type(df, "Advertiser")
print('Bottom 5 Advertisers by order type: \n', bottom_advertisers)

# Bottom 5 Sellers by Order Type

print('Bottom 5 Sellers by order type: \n', bottom_sellers)

# # Bottom 5 Products by Order Type
bottom_products = bottom_by_order_type(df, "Product")
print('Bottom 5 Products by order type: \n', bottom_products)

# -------------------------------
# Visualize Bottom 5 Example
# -------------------------------


def plot_bottom(df, group_col, title, bottom_n=5):
    subset = (
        df.groupby([group_col])["Sum of Gross Revenue"]
          .sum()
          .nsmallest(bottom_n)
          .reset_index()
    )
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
    sns.barplot(data=subset, x="Sum of Gross Revenue", y=group_col, palette="Reds_r")
    plt.title(f"Bottom {bottom_n} {group_col} by Revenue")
    plt.xlabel("Revenue")
    plt.ylabel(group_col)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Example: Bottom 10 Markets
plot_bottom(df, "Market", "Bottom Markets by Revenue", bottom_n=5)

# Train isolation forest
clf = IsolationForest(contamination=0.01, random_state=42)
df["anomaly"] = clf.fit_predict(df[["Sum of Gross Revenue"]])

# Count anomalies per market
outlier_counts = df.groupby("Market")["Sum of Gross Revenue"].count().sort_values(ascending=False).head(15)

# Bar chart
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
sns.barplot(x=outlier_counts.index, y=outlier_counts.values, color="red")
plt.title("Markets with Most AI-Flagged Revenue Outliers")
plt.ylabel("Number of Anomalies")
plt.xlabel("Market")
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha="right")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

AI-Assisted Insights¶

Using an AI model (Isolation Forest), we detected anomalies in revenue patterns. The bar highlights suspicious orders in red. The bar chart aggregates them, showing which markets have the highest concentration of anomalies. These could signal reporting errors, fraud, or exceptional one-off deals — all worth a closer look. Since quite a few of the highest outliers are not reported in the top performing market, below let's take a look at the bottom performing, just in case.

It appears that there is no relation between the outliers and bottom performing markets. Would recommend looking further in depth for the outliers situation.
